    <text>
        <body>
            <p style="text-align: left; ">
                <hi rend="background(white)" xml:space="preserve">Typical presentations at digital humanities (DH) conferences tend to emphasize research findings, often including only brief mentions of the underlying technical work. The </hi>
                <hi rend="bold background(white)">Digital Humanities Tech Symposium</hi>
                <hi rend="background(white)" xml:space="preserve"> intentionally inverts this format. It places the focus squarely on the technical aspects of digital humanities projects, while still situating them within their broader research and disciplinary contexts. This symposium provides a dedicated venue for in-depth discussion of the technologies that enable, support, and shape DH research.</hi>
            </p>
            <p style="text-align: left; ">Presentations at the Digital Humanities Tech Symposium highlight topics such as:</p>
            <list type="unordered">
                <item>Implementation and design details of research software, tools, and infrastructure</item>
                <item>Lessons learned from developing and maintaining DH software applications</item>
                <item>Tool demonstrations with a focus on technical functionality, architecture, and use cases</item>
                <item>Community building, sustainability, and diversity within the technical DH landscape</item>
            </list>
            <p style="text-align: left; ">In addition to traditional talks, the mini-conference will feature tool presentations, live demos, and other formats that suit the technical nature of the content. The goal is to foster practical knowledge exchange and professional connection among those working at the intersection of software development and the humanities.</p>
            <p style="text-align: left; ">
                <hi rend="background(white)">The Digital Humanities Tech Symposium is organized by DHTech</hi><ref n="1" target="ftn1"/>
                <hi rend="background(white)">, a Special Interest Group of the Alliance of Digital Humanities Organizations (ADHO). DHTech is an international community of DH practitioners who focus on the technical dimensions of digital humanities research. The symposium is one of several initiatives DHTech offers to support its members by providing a platform for networking, collaboration, and sharing technical expertise.</hi>
            </p>
        </body>
